malized": false, "mention": "eNOS", "obj": "gene", "prob": 0.7343637943267822, "span": {"begin": 503, "end": 507}}, {"id": ["NCBIGene:4846"], "is_neural_normalized": false, "mention": "eNOS", "obj": "gene", "prob": 0.9874375462532043, "span": {"begin": 523, "end": 527}}, {"id": ["mesh:D009569"], "is_neural_normalized": false, "mention": "NO", "obj": "drug", "prob": null, "span": {"begin": 570, "end": 572}}, {"id": ["mesh:D013481"], "is_neural_normalized": false, "mention": "superoxide", "obj": "drug", "prob": 0.9997621178627014, "span": {"begin": 609, "end": 619}}, {"id": ["mesh:D009569"], "is_neural_normalized": false, "mention": "NO", "obj": "drug", "prob": null, "span": {"begin": 673, "end": 675}}, {"id": ["mesh:D013481"], "is_neural_normalized": false, "mention": "superoxide", "obj": "drug", "prob": 0.9998196959495544, "span": {"begin": 680, "end": 690}}, {"id": ["mesh:D006973"], "is_neural_normalized": false, "mention": "hypertension", "obj": "disease", "prob": 0.999992847442627, "span": {"begin": 739, "end": 751}}, {"id": ["mim:108725", "mesh:D050197"], "is_neural_normalized": false, "mention": "atherosclerosis", "obj": "disease", "prob": 0.9999984502792358, "span": {"begin": 753, "end": 768}}, {"id": ["mesh:D006937"], "is_neural_normalized": false, "mention": "hypercholesterolemia", "obj": "disease", "prob": 0.999996542930603, "span": {"begin": 770, "end": 790}}, {"id": ["mesh:D003920"], "is_neural_normalized": false, "mention": "diabetes mellitus", "obj": "disease", "prob": 0.9999977350234985, "span": {"begin": 796, "end": 813}}], "text": "Nitric oxide (NO), constitutively produced by endothelial nitric oxide synthase (eNOS), is an important regulator of vascular homeostasis. Endothelial-derived NO promotes vasodilation and protects against atherogenesis through the inhibition of vascular smooth muscle cell proliferation and migration, platelet aggregation and adhesion, and leukocyte adherence. Its effects have an influence on vascular resistance, blood pressure, vascular remodeling and angiogenesis (Luo et al., 2000). Dysfunctional eNOS as a result of eNOS uncoupling leads to a decrease or loss of NO bioavailability and an elevation of superoxide production (Crabtree et al., 2009). The imbalance of NO and superoxide is associated with many disorders,&nbsp;such as hypertension, atherosclerosis, hypercholesterolemia, and diabetes mellitus.", "timestamp": "Fri May 15 21:38:11 +0000 2026"}